{"title_page": "ThinkPad X1 Carbon", "text_new": "{{infobox computer\n| name               = ThinkPad X1 Carbon\n| photo              = [[File:Lenovo ThinkPad X1 Ultrabook.jpg|frameless]]\n| caption            = Lenovo ThinkPad X1 Carbon (2012)\n| alt                =\n| developer          = [[Lenovo]]\n| family             = [[ThinkPad]]\n| releasedate        = {{release date and age|2012|08}}\n| type               = [[Ultrabook]] [[laptop computer]]\n| cpu                = [[Intel Core]]\n| predecessor        = [[ThinkPad X series#X1|ThinkPad X1]]\n}}\n\nThe '''[[ThinkPad]] X1 Carbon''' is a high-end 14-inch [[notebook computer]] released by [[Lenovo]] in 2012 and updated every year since 2014. The ThinkPad X1 Carbon Touch featured a [[multitouch]] enabled screen in order to take more effective advantage of [[Microsoft]]'s [[Windows 8]], [[Windows 8.1]], and [[Windows 10]] operating systems.\n\n==Launch==\nIn early August 2012, Lenovo released the [[ThinkPad]] X1 Carbon as the successor to the earlier ThinkPad X1.<ref name=CNET /> The X1 Carbon was first released in China due to the popularity of ThinkPads in that market.<ref name=\"CarbonWP\">{{cite news |title=Lenovo unveils lighter, quicker ThinkPad inspired by convenience of tablets, smart phones |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2012/08/06/lenovo-unveils-lighter-q_n_1746197.html |newspaper=[[The Huffington Post]] |date=6 August 2012 |accessdate=6 August 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref> In November 2012, Lenovo announced a touch-screen variant called the ThinkPad X1 Carbon Touch designed for use with Windows 8. Its display makes use of multi-touch technology that can detect simultaneous inputs from up to ten fingers. On the performance of the X1 Carbon Touch's SSD, [[Engadget]] states, \"The machine boots into the [s]tart screen in 11 seconds, which is pretty typical for a Windows 8 machine with specs like these. We also found that the solid-state drive delivers equally strong read and write speeds (551 MB/s and 518 MB/s, respectively), which we noticed the last time we tested an Ultrabook with an Intel SSD.\" boom \n\n==Models==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\" style=\"min-width: 75%; font-size: 80%;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"13\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | Lenovo ThinkPad X1 series and predecessors\n|-\n!\n!Type\n! colspan=\"2\" |X*0* <br/>(2008)\n!X*2* <br/>(2011)\n!X*3* <br/>(2012)\n!X*4* <br/>(2013)\n!(2014)\n!X*5* <br/>(2015)\n!X*6* <br/>(2016)\n!X*7* <br/>(2017)\n!X*8* <br/>(2018)\n!X*9* <br />(2019)\n|-\n|13\"\n|Premium\n|X300\n|X301\n|X1\n! colspan=\"8\" |\n|-\n| colspan=\"13\" |\n|-\n|12\"\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Tablet\n! colspan=\"7\" |\n|X1 Tablet Gen1\n|X1 Tablet Gen2\n! colspan=\"2\" |\n|-\n|13\"\n! colspan=\"9\" |\n|X1 Tablet Gen3\n| {{TBA}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |14\"\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Flipbook \u00ab2-in-1\u00bb\n! colspan=\"7\" |\n|[[ThinkPad Yoga#X1 Yoga|X1 Yoga Gen1]]\n|[[ThinkPad Yoga#X1 Yoga gen2|X1 Yoga Gen2]]\n|[[ThinkPad Yoga#X1 Yoga gen3|X1 Yoga Gen3]]\n|[[ThinkPad Yoga#X1 Yoga gen4|X1 Yoga Gen4]]\n|-\n! colspan=\"7\" |\n| rowspan=\"2\" |X1 Carbon<br>Gen4\n! colspan=\"3\" |\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Premium<br>ultrabook\n! colspan=\"3\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" |X1 Carbon Gen1\n|X1 Carbon Gen2\n|X1 Carbon Gen3\n|X1 Carbon Gen5\n|X1 Carbon Gen6\n|X1 Carbon Gen7\n|-\n|15\"\n! colspan=\"9\" |\n|X1 Carbon Extreme<br>Gen1\n|X1 Carbon Extreme<br>Gen2\n|-\n! colspan=\"13\" |'''Docking stations and port replicators compatibility (X1 Carbon series laptops only)'''\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |[[USB-C]] Dock\n! colspan=\"8\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" |X1 Carbon, X1 Carbon Extreme\n|\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |'''ThinkPad Basic Dock (USB-C)'''<br />'''ThinkPad Pro Dock (USB-C)<br />ThinkPad Ultra Dock (USB-C)'''\n! colspan=\"9\" |\n|X1 Carbon<br/>X1 Carbon Extreme\n|\n|-\n! colspan=\"13\" |X1 port replicators\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |ThinkPad OneLink Dock\n! colspan=\"5\" |\n| colspan=\"4\" |X1 Carbon\n! colspan=\"2\" |\n|}\n\n'''Battery configuration'''\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n